@next "WHY"
@endnode
@node WHY "Why"
@prev "MAIN"
I was quite happy with Backclock, until I got my graphics card and started experimenting with
CGX and P96. I noticed that each system displayed the clock slightly differently, with P96
displaying the quarter marks in a different colour to the hour marks, but CGX displayed them
all in the same colour. A quick look through the configuration options revealed that this was
 not a configurable item, and I started looking at what other configuration options were
 missing.

I also noticed that Backclock did not support full window dragging or closing. The only way
to quit it was to go through "Exchange". BBClock was born, filling in all the gaps in
Backclock.

@{"Back to main" link MAIN}
@endnode

@node REQUIREMENTS "Requirements"

* An Amiga (or emulator) running OS3.1 or higher (may work on earlier OS but not tested)
* MUI

@{"Back to main" link MAIN}

@endnode

@node INSTALLATION "Installation"

Copy BBClock and its' icon wherever you want (I suggest WBStartup). Copy BBClockPrefs wherever
you want (I suggest Workbenc/Prefs). Double click on BBClocks icon to start: Double click the
prefs icon to launch the prefs program.

@{"Back to main" link MAIN}

@endnode
@node CONFIGURATION "Configuration"

All the configuration options are stored in BBClocks' icon, with the exception of the window
size and position which are stored in a small config file in ENVARC: However, please don't
edit the tooltypes directly - and DON'T disable any of the tooltypes.

Much better (and easier) to use the prefs program, which will ensure that the correct format
of the tooltypes is preserved.

The left hnd column in the prefs program controls colours, and the right hand side controls
switches. Click on the colour preview box to change a colour - BBClock will react to the
change once the colour selector window is closed.

The various switches control the overall look of the program. Experiment until you get the
look you want.

Note: 3D has no effect unless "Solid" is enabled.

@{"Back to main" link MAIN}

@endnode


@node USAGE "Usage"

Double click the BBClock icon to start it. Clicking the top right hand corner of the window
will close it, resizing is done from the right hand edge of the window. Anywhere else moves
the clock.

For the prefs program, please ensure that BBClock is already running. If BBClock has been run
and quit, then the prefs program can still be used, but obviously there will be no realtime
update.

If BBClock has not been run before the prefs program, then the preferences will not be picked
up from the icon, nor will they be saved back to it - so there's no point really :o)

@{"Back to main" link MAIN}

@endnode
@node BUGS "Bugs"

Only two that I know of - and they are both the fault of the OS, not BBClock:-

* Constantly opening and closing an icons tooltypes can result in a small memory leak because
  the OS doesn't provide any way to release the memory used as a buffer. Ultimately, this can
  lead to a crash. Usually, you would only encounter this while using the prefs program. Once
  you have set up BBClock to your liking, it ceases to become an issue. If you are making
  extensive changes to the prefs, experimenting extensively with the options, you can help
  avoid problems by closing and re-starting the prefs program periodically.

* Whenever the clock has to be re-drawn in "Solid" mode, there is a small (approx 2k) memory
  overhead that I have been unable to recover. This only occurs when:-

  i) Moving/sizing the clock (in solid mode)
  ii) Turning second markers on/off (in solid mode)
  iii) Turning marker shadows on/off (in solid mode)

  If you prefer to run BBClock as a transparent clock, then this won't be an issue. Again,
  this will probably only be a problem until you have set the clock up to your liking. Once you
  have it configured, then the leak won't occur.

@{"Back to main" link MAIN}

@endnode

